The performance for Cr(VI) was evaluated (Fig. 7c–d). There was a good linear relationship between quenching efficiency and concentration of Cr(VI) in the range of 0.2–80 μM with a limit of detection of 0.11 μM (Fig. 7d). Although CE analysis confirmed the presence of multiple components in the prepared material, successful detection of Cr(VI) was still achieved without any negative effect from its complicated composition. The applicability of CNDs on the detection of Cr(VI) was proved with water and soil samples (Table 1
                        ). Cr(VI) in these samples was lower than LOD. The spiked Cr(VI) standards were reliably determined with recoveries ranging in 95.3–107%. RSDs (n = 3) are lower than 4.3%. Table 2
                         shows the comparison of other methods for the detection of Cr(VI). For fluorometry based on different nanomaterials, the method proposed in this work have low LOD which is lower than the maximum permissible Cr(VI) level of 50 μg/L (0.96 μM) in water [52].
